 {"id":"bd-1hk","title":"Implement auto-initialize client behavior","description":"# Auto-Initialize Client Behavior

## Background
Python FastMCP client automatically initializes when entering a context manager. Currently Rust requires manual client.initialize() call. Auto-initialize simplifies usage.

## Requirements

### ClientBuilder Configuration
```rust
impl ClientBuilder {
    /// Enable auto-initialization on first request
    /// Default: false (manual initialization required)
    pub fn auto_initialize(self, auto: bool) -> Self
}
```

### Auto-Initialize Behavior
When auto_initialize is enabled:
1. First method call (call_tool, read_resource, etc.) triggers initialize
2. Initialize happens lazily on first use
3. Subsequent calls skip initialization
4. Thread-safe initialization guard

```rust
impl Client {
    async fn ensure_initialized(&self, cx: Cx) -> McpResult<()> {
        if !self.initialized.load(Ordering::Acquire) {
            // Initialize with default client info
            self.initialize(cx, ClientInfo::default()).await?;
        }
        Ok(())
    }

    pub async fn call_tool(&self, cx: Cx, name: &str, args: Value) -> McpResult<CallToolResult> {
        if self.auto_initialize {
            self.ensure_initialized(cx).await?;
        }
        // ... existing implementation
    }
}
```

### Thread Safety
Use atomic flag for initialization state:
```rust
struct Client {
    initialized: AtomicBool,
    initializing: Mutex<()>, // Prevent concurrent init
    auto_initialize: bool,
}
```

## Testing
- Test auto-init happens on first call
- Test subsequent calls skip init
- Test concurrent calls don't race
- Test manual init still works

## Files to Modify
- crates/fastmcp-client/src/builder.rs
- crates/fastmcp-client/src/lib.rs

